<tr><td align="left" valign="bottom" width="98%"><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/toptab.gif" width="98" height="10" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0"></td><td align="left" valign="bottom" width="22">&nbsp;</td></tr>
<tr><td bgcolor="#3F403F" width="98%" class="cheader"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></td><td bgcolor="3F403F" valign="top" align="right" width="22"><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/topcorner.gif" width="23" height="22" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0" align="right"></td></tr>
<tr><td width="98%" colspan=2><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" class="cbody">
<tr><td><font class="h1font"> A Mathematician&#39;s View: Hits<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.50)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/swtcg/main/mpage.php?member=10789'>Chris "McLarenC" McLaren</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/swtcg/main/mpage.php?member=10789&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> May 28, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> 	This is the first article in my third series of articles on the Star Wars TCG.  Of course my first series covered the different themes of cards that exist in the game, and the second series, which will continue concurrently with this one, covers different elements that can be manipulated or controlled in the game such as force or build points and deck manipulation.  This article was the first that I wrote, but it originally included tables, which I had to devise a way of getting around to get the information across in this article.  So the information will be referenced parenthetically, much the same way I described the cards in my first two series of articles.  Now on to the article…<br>
	One thing that separates this game from other CCGs is the use of Dice.  And yes this is the subject of much debate over whether this is good or bad.  Like it or not, the game includes them, so it would benefit us to understand them.  It is not to difficult to understand that if you roll 1 die you have a probability of 0.5 to hit.  But judging by many of the posts about dice on the message boards that I have read, when more dice are used people get more confused a bout how many hits they should expect to get.<br>
	Expectation is easy, when you are rolling six dice you would expect three of them to “hit”.  When you are rolling any number of dice, you would expect half of them to hit.  However, in actuality, you will only get three hits a third of the time when rolling six dice.  But you would also get 2 and 4 hits roughly a quarter of the time.  As a matter of fact, you will get 2, 3 or 4 hits 78% of the time.  <br>
	The math is rather simple to figure out the number of hits that you will have.  It is a binomial distribution with p=0.5 and n equal to the number of dice you are rolling.  To find the probability of  x hits you multiply nCx times p^n, where nCx is the number of combinations of n things taken x at a time.  In English, this is the number ways to roll x hits in n rolls multiplied by 0.5 to the power of n.<br>
	For those who have trouble when it comes to math, I have included a table of percentages for powers of 1 through 12, these will be displayed as such: power: (probability of no hits, prob. of one hit, prob of 2 hits…) {Hopefully this is easy enough to follow}<br>
<br>
1:(50.00%,50.00%)<br>
2:(25.00%,50.00%,25.00%)<br>
3:(12.50%,37.50%,37.50%,12.50%)<br>
4:(6.25%,25.00%,37.50%,25.00%,6.25%)<br>
5:(3.13%,15.63%,31.25%,31.25%,15.63%,3.13%)<br>
6:(1.56%,9.38%,23.44%,31.25%,23.44%,9.38%,1.56%)<br>
7:(0.78%,5.47%,16.41%,27.34%,27.34%,16.41%,5.47%,0.78%)<br>
8:(0.39%,3.13%,10.94%,21.88%,27.34%,21.88%,10.94%,3.13%,0.39%)<br>
9:(0.20%,1.76%,7.03%,16.41%,24.61%,24.61%,16.41%,7.03%,1.76%,0.20%)<br>
10:(0.10%,0.98%,4.39%,11.72%,20.51%,24.61%,20.51%,11.72%,4.39%,0.98%,0.10%)<br>
11:(0.05%,0.54%,2.69%,8.06%,16.11%,22.56%,22.56%,16.11%,8.06%,2.69%,0.54%,0.05%)<br>
12:(0.02%,0.29%,1.61%,5.37%,12.08%,19.34%,22.56%,19.34%,12.08%,5.37%,1.61%,0.29%,0.02%)<br>
<br>
	Note a few things: First look at how, especially at higher powers, how the probability is sharply concentrated near the middle of the possible values.  This is what you need to strategize to, over the long term you would expect hit half the time.  But don’t fall into looking for ships to be “due” to hit, or expect something to happen based on what you have seen already, each roll of the dice is a new and independent event.  Secondly, the probability of hitting with all of your dice is the same as missing with all of your dice.  Hitting with one die is the same as missing with one die.  This symmetry is present because your chances of hitting and missing are both 0.5.  Because of this symmetry, a cumulative table is helpful as well.  This shows the chances of hitting with x number of dice or less.<br>
<br>
1:(50.00%,100.00%)<br>
2:(25.00%,75.00%,100.00%,)<br>
3:(12.50%,50.00%,87.50%,100.00%)<br>
4:(6.25%,31.25%,68.75%,93.75%,100.00%)<br>
5:(3.13%,18.75%,50.00%,81.25%,96.88%,100.00%)<br>
6:(1.56%,10.94%,34.38%,65.63%,89.06%,98.44%,100.00%)<br>
7:(0.78%,6.25%,22.66%,50.00%,77.34%,93.75%,99.22%,100.00%)<br>
8:(0.39%,3.52%,14.45%,36.33%,63.67%,85.55%,96.48%,99.61%,100.00%)<br>
9:(0.20%,1.95%,8.98%,25.39%,50.00%,74.61%,91.02%,98.05%,99.80%,100.00%)<br>
10:(0.10%,1.07%,5.47%,17.19%,37.70%,62.30%,82.81%,94.53%,98.93%,99.90%,100.00%)<br>
11:(0.05%,0.59%,3.27%,11.33%,27.44%,50.00%,72.56%,88.67%,96.73%,99.41%,99.95%,100.00%)<br>
12:(0.02%,0.32%,1.93%,7.30%,19.38%,38.72%,61.28%,80.62%,92.70%,98.07%,99.68%,99.98%,100.00%)<br>
<br>
	Due again to the symmetry involved, this table can also be looked at as describing the Probability of x misses or less.  This allows this table to be used to find things like the probability of 1 or more hits by looking at the probability of no hits, or the first column of the table. <br>
	I hope that this will aid a bit in your understanding of how the dice will “work” in a given situation.  There is more to this and in future installments I will look at the chances of one unit defeating another in one on one combat, and even possibly generalize it a bit.  In my opinion, there is plenty of room for strategy in this game and the dice are actually a “source” of some of this strategy.  It is a lot harder for your strategy to adapt to the added randomness of dice.  I also plan to look at how math (both simple and at times complex) can aid in ones understanding of how the game works.  <br>
	If you have any suggestions, or would like to pose a question that you would like addressed, feel free to contact me.  For those interested in working out some of this on their own, most of what I will be doing can be accomplished in a simple spreadsheet.  Personally, I used MS Excel for my calculations here, if you would like to know more let me know.  In addition, I am toying with the idea of putting all of my articles, and some of my supporting spreadsheets and databases, up on a web site, but I am not sure of that.  If I do do that I will alert you to that fact in my personal page.<br>
<br>
